body:
hi @caarlos0 

I do vote for the GOOS/GOARCH values since they are stable and consistent (and short).

If you don't have a replacements section, you know exactly what will be the output (GOOS values)

If you don't like that, you can over-ride exactly what you'd like.  No surprises in output (GOOS and anything you replaced)

Love the idea here:

curl https://blah/myapp_$(uname -s)_$(uname -m).tar.gz

but it's not portable.  Check out I looked at what https://glide.sh/get does to turn uname values into GOOS/GOARCH values.

"amd64" has 2 variations
"386" has 3
arm looks like a mess

I have similar functions in my code (not as complete however).

```
initArch() {
        ARCH=$(uname -m)
        case $ARCH in
                armv5*) ARCH="armv5";;
                armv6*) ARCH="armv6";;
                armv7*) ARCH="armv7";;
                aarch64) ARCH="arm64";;
                x86) ARCH="386";;
                x86_64) ARCH="amd64";;
                i686) ARCH="386";;
                i386) ARCH="386";;
        esac
}

initOS() {
        OS=$(echo `uname`|tr '[:upper:]' '[:lower:]')

        case "$OS" in
                # Minimalist GNU for Windows
                mingw*) OS='windows';;
        esac
}
```

Otherwise for "godownloader" i have to look at "do they have replacements, do this.  If they don't do that"  Not the end of the world to do this.  I can adjust to anything we come up with!
